    {"question": "What is transverse momentum in particle physics experiments?", "ground_truth": "Transverse momentum (pT) is the component of a particle's momentum perpendicular to the beam axis. It is conserved in the transverse plane of a collision, making missing transverse momentum a key signature for undetected particles like neutrinos or dark matter candidates."},
    {"question": "What is the pseudorapidity variable used in collider physics?", "ground_truth": "Pseudorapidity η = -ln(tan(θ/2)) where θ is the polar angle from the beam axis. It approximates rapidity for massless particles and is preferred over angle because differences in η are Lorentz-invariant under boosts. The LHC detectors cover |η| < 5 typically."},
    {"question": "What is top quark pair production at the LHC?", "ground_truth": "Top quarks are the heaviest known fundamental particles (mt ≈ 173 GeV) and are produced predominantly in pairs (tt̄) via gluon-gluon fusion at the LHC. They decay almost exclusively to a W boson and a b quark before hadronisation, providing a clean experimental signature."},
    {"question": "What is the purpose of the LHCb experiment?", "ground_truth": "LHCb is a single-arm forward spectrometer at the LHC dedicated to studying heavy-flavor physics, particularly B-meson and D-meson decays, to measure CP violation and rare decays with high precision, testing the Standard Model and searching for new physics in flavor sector."},
    {"question": "What are jets in particle physics?", "ground_truth": "Jets are collimated sprays of hadrons produced by the fragmentation and hadronisation of quarks or gluons. They are reconstructed from calorimeter deposits using clustering algorithms like anti-kT. Jet energy scale calibration is a critical systematic uncertainty in many LHC measurements."},
    {"question": "What is pileup in LHC experiments?", "ground_truth": "Pileup refers to additional proton-proton interactions per beam crossing beyond the primary hard scatter event. At high luminosity, 50-140 simultaneous interactions occur per crossing, complicating event reconstruction. Pileup mitigation techniques include vertex identification and jet area subtraction."},
    {"question": "What is the Drell-Yan process?", "ground_truth": "The Drell-Yan process is the production of a virtual photon or Z boson via quark-antiquark annihilation (qq̄ → γ*/Z → l⁺l⁻), resulting in a lepton pair. It is a benchmark process at the LHC for measuring parton distribution functions and electroweak parameters."},
    {"question": "What are parton distribution functions (PDFs)?", "ground_truth": "PDFs describe the probability of finding a parton (quark or gluon) carrying a fraction x of the proton's momentum at a given energy scale Q². They are extracted from deep inelastic scattering and other hard-scattering data and are essential inputs to all LHC cross-section calculations."},
    {"question": "What is the LHC injection chain?", "ground_truth": "Protons begin in Linac4 (50 MeV), transfer to the Proton Synchrotron Booster (1.4 GeV), then the Proton Synchrotron (25 GeV), then the Super Proton Synchrotron (450 GeV), before final injection and acceleration to 6.8 TeV per beam in the LHC ring."},
    {"question": "What is a silicon vertex detector?", "ground_truth": "Silicon vertex detectors (e.g., ATLAS IBL, CMS pixel tracker) are innermost tracking devices providing high-spatial-resolution hit measurements closest to the interaction point. They enable reconstruction of secondary vertices from B-hadron decays (b-tagging) critical for Higgs and top physics."},
