    {"question": "What is the ALICE detector used for?", "ground_truth": "ALICE (A Large Ion Collider Experiment) is the dedicated heavy-ion experiment at the LHC, studying quark-gluon plasma formation in Pb-Pb, Xe-Xe, and p-Pb collisions. Its specialized detectors (TPC, ITS, TOF, EMCAL) measure particle multiplicities, spectra, and collective flow phenomena."},
    {"question": "What is CP violation in particle physics?", "ground_truth": "CP violation is the asymmetry between matter (C: charge conjugation) and antimatter (P: parity reversal). It is observed in K and B meson systems and is necessary for the matter-antimatter asymmetry in the universe. The Standard Model describes it via the CKM matrix phase."},
    {"question": "What is the role of the trigger system at LHC experiments?", "ground_truth": "LHC experiments use multi-level trigger systems to select interesting collision events from the 40 MHz bunch crossing rate. ATLAS/CMS use a hardware Level-1 trigger (~100 kHz) followed by a High Level Trigger running software algorithms to reduce the rate to ~1 kHz for permanent storage."},
    {"question": "What is missing transverse energy (MET) in collider experiments?", "ground_truth": "Missing transverse energy (ETmiss or MET) is the negative vector sum of all visible particle transverse momenta in an event. Non-zero MET indicates undetected particles escaping the detector, such as neutrinos or BSM weakly-interacting particles, making it a key dark matter search variable."},
    {"question": "What is the LHC cryogenic system?", "ground_truth": "The LHC cryogenic system maintains 1,746 superconducting magnets at 1.9K (below superfluid helium transition) using the world's largest cryogenic installation with ~130 tonnes of helium. The system requires 6-8 weeks to cool down the 27 km ring and consumes ~40 MW of power."},
    {"question": "What is the beam emittance in accelerator physics?", "ground_truth": "Beam emittance is a measure of the phase-space area occupied by beam particles, quantifying the beam's spread in position and momentum. Smaller emittance means a more focused beam with higher luminosity. LHC proton beams have normalized emittance ~2-3 μm at injection, compressed during acceleration."},
    {"question": "What are the main physics goals of the High-Luminosity LHC (HL-LHC)?", "ground_truth": "The HL-LHC aims to increase integrated luminosity to 3000 fb⁻¹ (10× Run 2-3) by 2040, enabling precision Higgs boson coupling measurements at 1-2% level, rare H→μμ and H→Zγ observation, search for di-Higgs production, and BSM physics sensitivity reaching ~3 TeV in pair production."},
    {"question": "What is a calorimeter in particle physics?", "ground_truth": "A calorimeter measures particle energy by total absorption. Electromagnetic calorimeters (ECAL) measure photons and electrons via electromagnetic showers; hadronic calorimeters (HCAL) measure hadron jets. ATLAS uses liquid argon ECAL; CMS uses lead tungstate (PbWO₄) crystals for its ECAL."},
    {"question": "What is the muon spectrometer in ATLAS?", "ground_truth": "The ATLAS muon spectrometer is the outermost detector system, using monitored drift tubes (MDT), cathode strip chambers (CSC), resistive plate chambers (RPC), and thin gap chambers (TGC) to track muons that escape the calorimeters. It covers |η|<2.7 and provides momentum resolution ~3% at 100 GeV."},
    {"question": "What is the strong coupling constant αs?", "ground_truth": "The strong coupling constant αs governs the strength of the strong nuclear force (QCD). At the Z boson mass scale, αs(MZ) ≈ 0.1179 ± 0.0010. It runs with energy scale (asymptotic freedom): decreasing at high energies allowing perturbative QCD calculations, and increasing at low energies causing confinement."},
    {"question": "What is the W boson mass anomaly?", "ground_truth": "In 2022, the CDF collaboration at Fermilab reported the W boson mass as 80,433.5 ± 9.4 MeV, significantly higher than the Standard Model prediction of ~80,357 MeV (7-sigma tension). Subsequent measurements by ATLAS and LHCb have not confirmed this discrepancy, leaving the situation unresolved."},
    {"question": "What is the role of the beam pipe at the LHC?", "ground_truth": "The LHC beam pipe is an ultra-high vacuum (10⁻¹⁰ to 10⁻¹¹ torr) tube through which proton beams circulate. The 27 km pipe is made of stainless steel with a beryllium section inside detectors for minimal material. Cold bore sections are cooled by liquid helium to reduce residual gas and synchrotron radiation effects."},
    {"question": "What is synchrotron radiation?", "ground_truth": "Synchrotron radiation is electromagnetic radiation emitted when charged particles are accelerated centripetally in magnetic fields. At the LHC, protons lose ~6.7 keV per revolution, requiring RF cavities to replenish energy. Synchrotron radiation is also exploited at dedicated light sources (ESRF, Diamond) for materials science."},
    {"question": "What is the inner tracking system of the CMS detector?", "ground_truth": "CMS inner tracker consists of a silicon pixel detector (close to interaction point, 3-4 layers) and silicon strip tracker (outer layers). The Phase-2 upgrade replaces all silicon with an all-pixel tracker covering |η|<4, providing hit information at 40 MHz for the HL-LHC Level-1 trigger."},
    {"question": "What are forward detectors at the LHC?", "ground_truth": "Forward detectors at the LHC cover very small angles near the beam (|η|>3.5), measuring forward hadron production, diffractive physics, and total cross-sections. Examples include TOTEM (total cross-section), AFP/ALFA (proton tagging), LHCf (cosmic ray calibration), and FASER (light dark matter)."},
    {"question": "What is a parton shower in Monte Carlo simulation?", "ground_truth": "Parton shower simulation models the QCD radiation of quarks and gluons as they propagate after the hard scatter, before hadronisation. It implements DGLAP evolution equations to produce additional gluon/quark emissions. Programs like Pythia8 and Herwig7 provide parton shower models matched to matrix element generators."},
    {"question": "What is the LHCb VELO detector?", "ground_truth": "VELO (Vertex Locator) is LHCb's silicon vertex detector located 5mm from the beam. It measures B-hadron decay vertices with ~20 μm impact parameter resolution, enabling b-tagging and lifetime measurements. The VELO uses 52 silicon strip sensors in a retractable design that moves close to the beam during stable conditions."},
    {"question": "What is the ATLAS liquid argon calorimeter?", "ground_truth": "The ATLAS liquid argon (LAr) calorimeter uses liquid argon as active material with lead absorbers for the ECAL and copper/tungsten for the HCAL forward regions. Cooled to 87K, it provides energy resolution σE/E ~ 10%/√E ⊕ 0.7% for electromagnetic measurements and covers |η|<4.9."},
    {"question": "What is a diffractive process at the LHC?", "ground_truth": "Diffractive processes occur when one or both protons survive the collision intact, exchanging a colorless object (Pomeron) with the struck proton remaining in the beam. Single diffraction, double diffraction, and central exclusive production are studied to understand soft QCD and Pomeron structure."},
    {"question": "What is the role of the SPS in the CERN accelerator complex?", "ground_truth": "The Super Proton Synchrotron (SPS) is a 6.9 km circumference accelerator serving as the final pre-injector for the LHC, accelerating protons to 450 GeV before injection. Historically it discovered the W and Z bosons (1983). The SPS also supplies beam to the North Area fixed-target experiments (NA61, NA62, NA64)."},
    {"question": "What is flavour physics and why is it important?", "ground_truth": "Flavour physics studies transitions between different quark/lepton generations, governed by the CKM matrix (quarks) and PMNS matrix (neutrinos). Rare decays and CP violation measurements in B, D, and K systems probe virtual BSM contributions beyond LHC kinematic reach, complementing direct searches."},
    {"question": "What is the precision electroweak measurement program at LEP?", "ground_truth": "LEP (Large Electron-Positron Collider, 1989-2000) at CERN produced ~17 million Z bosons and measured electroweak observables with per-mille precision: Z mass (91187.6 ± 2.1 MeV), width, sin²θW, number of light neutrino species (Nν=3), and W boson mass, providing the precision SM baseline still used today."},
    {"question": "What are long-lived particles (LLPs) and how are they searched for at the LHC?", "ground_truth": "Long-lived particles have lifetimes producing macroscopic decay lengths (mm to km). LLP searches at ATLAS/CMS use displaced vertices, delayed signals, and non-standard signatures in detector regions. Dedicated experiments like FASER and MoEDAL extend LLP sensitivity to very weakly-coupled dark sector mediators."},
    {"question": "What is the HL-LHC ATLAS Inner Tracker (ITk) upgrade?", "ground_truth": "ITk is the all-silicon inner tracker replacing ATLAS's current TRT and SCT for the HL-LHC. It has 5 pixel layers (including MAPS pixel technology) and 4 strip layers, covering |η|<4. ITk handles 200 simultaneous pileup interactions and improves b-tagging and track reconstruction at HL-LHC luminosity."},
